[approval_required]
This iteration's plan needs user sign-off on the mission
contract — `mission_goal` + the structured acceptance
criteria list. The `mission:validate_and_approve` call you
make to submit the plan ALSO runs that approval.

The tool atomically: (a) validates the plan shape — invalid
returns `{ valid: false, errors: [...] }` and you fix +
re-call; (b) decides whether the user needs to see a modal
this iteration (see rules below); (c) returns
`{ valid: true, approved: bool, refine_text?: string,
   aborted?: bool, reason?: string }`.

The runtime opens the approval modal when one of these is
true; otherwise the call returns `approved: true` silently
and the prior approval stands:

- First plan in this mission — no approval on file yet, so
  the user MUST see the first plan.
- A worker downstream emitted `invalidates_plan_approval:
  true` (and optionally `invalidates_reason: "<short
  text>"`) — the runtime carries that signal until the next
  modal closes approve.
- This body sets `requires_reapproval: true` — you, the
  planner, are signalling that something material changed
  since the last approved iteration.
- Auto-promote: this body carries ANY contract-change
  diff — `ac_add` entries OR `ac_update` entries with
  `statement` or `drop` set. The runtime opens the modal
  even when you forgot the flag (contract changes always
  need user sign-off).

Set `body.requires_reapproval: true` ONLY when the strategic
contract changed since the user's last approval — and pair
it with `body.reapproval_reason: "<one short sentence>"` so
the user understands what changed. Cosmetic re-wording of
`mission_goal` does NOT warrant re-approval; keep the user's
signed-off contract intact. Status-only `ac_update` entries
(marking ids satisfied / unsatisfied without rewriting the
statement) also pass silently — they're status tracking,
not contract changes.

Response branches:

- `approved: true` → you are DONE. Reply with just `done`.
- `refine_text` populated (or any free-form non-approve
  reply) → the user wants edits. Revise per the text, then
  re-call `mission:validate_and_approve` with the revised
  body. Don't loop forever — three revise cycles is a sign
  to step back and ask the user a clarifying inquiry
  instead.
- `aborted: true` → the user wants out. Reply with just
  `done`; the runtime terminates the mission as cancelled.

Quality checks (the runtime won't enforce these, but the user
sees them in the modal):

- `body.mission_goal` must be a single concise sentence —
  the user reads it as the headline of the modal.
- Every `ac_add[i].statement` must be a short, singularly-
  satisfiable statement — the user scans them to decide
  whether to approve.
- `body.rationale` must be one or two clear sentences — the
  user reads them as the inquire's Context.
- Every roadmap entry must carry a short `description` so
  the inquire lists the bigger picture, not just the next
  wave.
{{end}}{{if .PendingReapproval}}
